Patch Set 1:

Couple of observations:
1. The Service Property/Service Instance drop down box seems to remain greyed out even when there is valid options to select from
2. Does the selection of a Service Input from a VF instance make sense, should it not be only possible to select an input from self. The generated tosca does not connect the input to be retrieved to an instance
3. For get_property for a property on the service itself (as opposed to a VF instance) the first element in the generated tosca is the name of the service - should this not be 'SELF'
4. - select a VF instance
   - open the 'Directives and Node Filter' tab
   - then add a new VF instance to the composition
   - then add a node filter to the already selected VF
   - the newly added VF does not appear in the Source drop down
Some of these are possibly faults in the existing implementation and can be taken in separate bugs if that is the case

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

please assign correct Issue-ID

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

> Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> 
> please assign correct Issue-ID

In general we don't use Issue-ID in OOM. We place them only to make gerrit auto-checks happy

Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

> Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1
> 
> > Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> > 
> > please assign correct Issue-ID
> 
> In general we don't use Issue-ID in OOM. We place them only to make gerrit auto-checks happy

hard to agree with this not 'good practice', and those changes just 'for change', and instead of fixing/solving outdated filebeat-images with unsupported Python 2, those commits disabling creation of logs and nobody knows reason or 'why', and what is the plan, are you going to replace filebeat with something?, are you going to upgrade to latest version?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1: -Code-Review
> 
> > Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1
> > 
> > > Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> > > 
> > > please assign correct Issue-ID
> > 
> > In general we don't use Issue-ID in OOM. We place them only to make gerrit auto-checks happy
> 
> hard to agree with this not 'good practice', and those changes just 'for change', and instead of fixing/solving outdated filebeat-images with unsupported Python 2, those commits disabling creation of logs and nobody knows reason or 'why', and what is the plan, are you going to replace filebeat with something?, are you going to upgrade to latest version?

I understand your concerns. Together with Sylvain we just find it super difficult and fragile to use Jira to document our features. We tend to prefer good commit messages and make sure that the documentation is as close to the code as possible (either directly in comment to template or in RTD).

Nothing is getting disabled in those commit. Just the ability to disable all filebeat sidecars with one option is added but the default behavior (as is now) is preserved.

We would love to upgrade this but there is a license issue in newer filebeat versions. Those new containers includes some non-open source components which would be incompatible with the ONAP license policy
